File-by-file purpose
aiHealing.ts — The AI tier. Builds a multimodal prompt (DOM-as-text + three real image blocks: old element, old page, current page) and asks GPT-4.1 for a Playwright locator as strict JSON. The imageBlock helper returns null for missing screenshots so empty blocks aren't sent (your screenshot fix). Low detail for reference images, high detail for the current page (token cost optimization). Strips markdown fences before JSON.parse.
BrowserActionImpl.ts — Concrete BrowserAction implementation. Each interaction (click/type/select) tries the primary locator, and on failure calls findWithFallback. Key logic: it only captures-and-stores a NEW element when !usedFallback and the element isn't already in the DB — preventing healed locators from overwriting baselines. WeakMap maps locators back to element names.
browserActions.ts — The interface contract. Pure types.
db.ts — Postgres pool (hardcoded creds — move to .env).
elementRepo.ts — saveElement upserts on element_name conflict, using COALESCE(NULLIF(...)) so blank/null incoming values don't wipe existing screenshots/HTML. getElement fetches by name.
healingRepo.ts — Append-only audit log of every healing attempt.
fallbackEngine.ts — The three-tier resolver: DB primary → smart locators (priority order) → AI heal. buildLocator/buildBaseLocator parse stored locator strings back into Playwright locators (your regex-name getByRole fix and >> visible=true / >> nth= suffix handling live here). isValidLocator accepts the "one-of-N-visible twin" and "soft match" cases. resolveToSingle narrows to the visible/first match.
selfHealing.ts — Locator-generation engine. Extracts element meta + ancestors/siblings, generates a bundle of smart locators (role/testId/label/placeholder/text/alt/title/css/xpath), each validated for uniqueness with the twin-aware verdictForLocator. Rejects dynamic IDs/indexed XPath. Captures element + full-page screenshots (JPEG q70) and minimal DOM.
flowTracker.ts / sink.ts — Both flow recorders (see bug #1). flowTracker upserts by elementName into flows/; sink pushes per-worker shards into shards/.
SelfHealingReporter.ts — Merges flows/ shards (only), dedupes by elementName, renders dashboard.
renderHtml.ts — Builds the themed dashboard (resilience ring, tier distribution, per-element expandable traces).

stepRunner.ts — Orchestrates the spec: overlay/popup dismissal (dismissWelcomePopup, forceRemoveOverlay), ensureSearchPanelOpen precondition, firstVisible candidate resolver, step() which routes capture-vs-resolve-vs-heal, and the typed errors (OverlayInterceptError, CaptureFailedError) that prevent wasting a healing cycle on problems AI can't fix.







The core flow — "walk me through what happens when a locator breaks"
The single most likely opening question. The path is:
step() in stepRunner.ts → checks DB for the element → if new, capture; if existing, resolveFromDB() → if that fails, findWithFallback() in fallbackEngine.ts → which runs DB primary → smart locators → AI healing.
Be ready to draw the three tiers and name the function for each: tier 1 and 2 are in both resolveFromDB() (stepRunner.ts) and findWithFallback() (fallbackEngine.ts). That's worth understanding because it's a redundancy a manager might catch — stepRunner tries DB/smart itself first via resolveFromDB, and only if that returns null does it call findWithFallback, which also tries DB/smart again before reaching AI. So in the resolve path, tiers 1–2 can run twice. Your defensible answer: resolveFromDB is the fast path during normal resolution; findWithFallback is the full chain invoked specifically when resolution has already failed and AI is the real target, and it re-checks DB/smart as a safety net. If he pushes, concede it's slightly redundant and could be refactored — don't pretend it's intentional optimization.
"How do you generate the smart locators? What stops them being flaky?"
Point to generateSmartLocators() in selfHealing.ts. Walk the priority order (role → testId → label → placeholder → text → alt → title → css → xpath) and explain why that order: accessibility-first locators (role/label) survive restyling better than CSS/XPath, which is also Playwright's own recommended priority.
The flakiness defense is two functions: isCleanValue() and isLikelyDynamicValue(). Be ready to recite what isLikelyDynamicValue rejects — UUIDs, 20+ char mixed-case-with-digits strings, framework prefixes (react/mui/mat/cdk/ng + digit), trailing large numbers, long hex hashes. And isStableXpath() rejecting positional/indexed XPath ([2], position(), last()). The concrete story that sells it: the comment in generateStableCss() about Ann Taylor's search input id flipping between #Submit-search and none — that's why bare id was demoted from a CSS strategy. Real bug, real fix, named in code.
"What's this twin / soft-match thing?"
This is your strongest "I understand the edge cases" answer. Three functions tell the story: verdictForLocator() in selfHealing.ts, and isValidLocator() + resolveToSingle() in fallbackEngine.ts.
The problem: a selector matching 2 elements is normally "not unique = reject." But retail sites render the same control twice (mobile + desktop), so a naive count-based check throws away a perfectly usable locator. The verdict system returns unique / visible-one / no. visible-one appends >> visible=true so the locator resolves to the visible twin at action time. Then the soft match case (product cards where image + title + quick-view all share one accessible name and all navigate to the same PDP) — several visible, all valid — is accepted with .first() but logged with a loud warning so it's auditable. Manager-pleasing detail: you didn't silently accept ambiguity, you accepted it and flagged it in the report.
"Why send screenshots to the AI? Isn't the DOM enough?"
aiHealing.ts, the prompt construction. The DOM tells the model structure; the screenshots give it visual + positional grounding to map "the element that looked like this and was here" to its new location. Point to the three image blocks (old element, old page, current page) and the imageBlock() helper. The cost-awareness answer that lands well: reference images go low detail, the current page goes high — because that's the one the model must search within, and detail level is a direct token-cost lever. Also note the null-filtering so missing screenshots don't become empty blocks. That was a real fix — the prompt used to paste base64/"Not available" text inline.
"How do you stop the AI from returning garbage?"
Three guards in findWithFallback(), after the AI call: the confidence threshold (< 0.7 throws), containsDynamicId() rejection (AI isn't allowed to hand back a dynamic locator either), and final isValidLocator() on the live page. So even a confident AI answer must actually resolve to a usable element before it's accepted. The AI doesn't get to "win" just by responding.
"How do I turn self-healing on and off?"
Be careful here — this is where the honest answer protects you. The real toggle is CAPTURE_MODE (read in stepRunner.ts), which forces capture-only. ENABLE_SELF_HEALING and ENABLE_LOCATOR_SYNC are in .env but not read anywhere in code — say that plainly. If you claim ENABLE_SELF_HEALING=false disables healing and he tests it, it won't, and that's worse than admitting it's unwired. The clean answer: "The active switches are CAPTURE_MODE and the in-run capturedThisRun guard. The env flags are placeholders; a real AI kill-switch would be a guard in findWithFallback before the AI tier — that's a tracked follow-up." (Your memory of a DISABLE_HEALING guard in fallbackEngine.ts — it's not in the version you pasted, so don't claim it's there.)
"What was the search_input bug?" — the capturedThisRun guard
The big comment block in stepRunner.ts. The story: capturing an element persists its DB row mid-run. Without the guard, a later step for the same element sees "row exists → existing → resolve/heal path" — but the page has since navigated, so resolution runs against the wrong state. capturedThisRun (an in-memory Set) guarantees once-captured-stays-captured for the run. This is a great answer because it shows you debugged a real stateful timing issue, not just wired up a library.
"What's the overlay handling for?"
dismissWelcomePopup() / forceRemoveOverlay() / runActionGuarded() in stepRunner.ts. The EShopWorld geo modal intercepts pointer events, so clicks time out even when the locator is correct. Key insight to convey: the framework distinguishes "locator wrong" (heal it) from "overlay blocked a correct locator" (don't heal — clear the overlay). That's OverlayInterceptError. Healing a correct locator would waste a full AI timeout and possibly corrupt the stored locator. Same logic for CaptureFailedError — nothing stored means nothing to heal.
